That's half of it IMHO. The other half is to encourage it to choose that path
by making your sensitive parts appear to have a high impedance.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; What I'd like to see is the sharing of experiences with EMI
&gt; (especically EFT/CI/RFI).
">

My last real job was on a new generation of PLC type product. The previous
generation had a reputation of not being very robust. So the new one had to
be super tough. We probably put a couple of man-years into studying what
worked and what didn't in our lab. We built NEMA and IEC standard test
gear, had scopes in faraday cages, built ESD guns and so on.

What came out of it for me, was an intuitive feel for how to solve or rather,
prevent noise issues.

A few general sweeping statements -
What works for ESD will also be effective for RFI. What works for RF
coming in will also be effective for RF going out.
Keep currents out. A static discharge is a current pulse. Current
magnetically couples and a magnetic field is very hard to suppress. Distance
is your best defence against magnetic coupling.

Consider everything from a high frequency electric field's perspective. What
does it 'see' as being high impedance and what is low impedance ?
Keep thinking &quot;voltage division&quot;. It is the key that everyone misses.

If you have a voltage divider with a high impedance in the top and a low
impedance in the bottom, the result is a low voltage on the output. If you just
have a high impedance and no low impedance to ground, you haven't
achieved anything.
Putting that into the context of noise reduction - A wire with a ferrite bead or
a track over a ground plane are not very effective on their own. Put the two
together and you get a result.

We got a pretty good result with the controller too. It had memory mirroring
(each word/byte compared at each fetch) and a latching watchdog that
required a manual reset to clear, so it would be pretty hard for a glitch to go
undetected.
We could run a 6&quot; spark down the outside of the case and blew up the
CPU's serial port (with no optos) by putting 240VAC on it and it never
missed a beat. We performed countless other attrocities too. EMC can be
fun.

Nearly all of that was from layout techniques and simple components like
R's and C's. It can be done.

Steve.
